{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Daniel (Michelangelo).jpg | title=The Prophet Daniel | artist=Michelangelo | year=circa 1508–1512 | type=Fresco | height_metric=390 | width_metric=380 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=[[Vatican City]] | museum=[[Sistine Chapel]], [[Vatican Palace]] }}
'''''The Prophet Daniel''''' is one of the seven [[Old Testament]] [[prophet]]'s painted by the [[Italians|Italian]] [[High Renaissance]] master [[Michelangelo]] (c. 1542–1545) on the [[Sistine Chapel ceiling]]. The [[Sistine Chapel]] is in [[Vatican Palace]], in the [[Vatican City]].
This particular [[fresco]] figure is painted second on the right from the side of the [[High Altar]]. Unlike many other paintings of the period, this portrayal makes no reference to the most famous event from [[Daniel (biblical figure)|Daniel]]'s life, that is his time [[Daniel in the lions' den|in the den of the lions]]. Instead, Michelangelo shows Daniel reading a great book, which is held up by a muscular figure from below.
